<h2>Often Overlooked Details</h2>
<p><strong>Alert thresholds aren't static</strong>. During sales events or new campaign ramp-up periods, burn rates may double. Dynamic threshold adjustment is necessary. Recommend recalibrating weekly based on spending volatility.</p>
<p><strong>Alert prioritization for multi-account teams</strong>. When managing multiple accounts, assign different alert urgency levels. Primary accounts can be more sensitive; secondary accounts can be more lenient. Prevents finance teams from alert fatigue when all accounts trigger simultaneously.</p>
<p><strong>Platform billing delays matter</strong>. Platforms like Meta have billing latency—actual spend may lag behind platform displays. Build 10-15% buffer into alert calculations.</p>
<h2>Quick Take</h2>
<p>Balance alerts are fundamentally risk management, not just a finance issue. The cost of one unexpected campaign pause often far exceeds recharge fees. The investment in building alert systems is minimal; the risk of neglect is substantial.</p>
